Democracy without popular connection
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and this has occurred everywhere in the world.
Somehow, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of elections to the European Parliament, the voter turnout was so absurdly low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Apart from voter turnout, we have grown accustomed to accepting parties or candidates who receive 25% of the votes as "winners."
Majority governments are formed based on minorities, from Holland via Finland to Argentina and Japan.
Even apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents have been elected by more than 10% of the electorate. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the USA have not even registered to vote; of those who did register, half do not vote; and of those who do vote, less than half vote for the winning candidate.
Even Tony Blair's "dam-break-like" majority in the UK House of Commons is standing on shaky ground: The Labour Party received only just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Accordingly, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, the situation with elections looks quite different from what it was twenty, or even fifty, years ago.
What happened?
One possible answer is that voters distrust the political parties.
The electoral democracy functions in most countries due to the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who advocate for specific packages of political options, a "manifesto" or an "election program."
For a number of reasons, this long-established practice no longer functions.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages put together by the parties, they want to pick out and choose things for themselves.
Moreover, political parties became machines composed of tightly organized inner circles of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voters.
Because most people don't want to belong to any particular party, only a minority is now playing the party game.
Thus, public suspicion toward political parties grows, not least because, like in professional sports, it is expensive to participate.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, it is resented.
Yet without financial support from the state, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often highly questionable, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators - such as the clear decline in memberships - confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because the parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the crucial institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and thus have the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, quite independent development comes into play.
People are more impatient today than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
But they must wait as voters before they can feel the results of the election they have cast at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful consideration.
However, the consumer as a voter will not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. However, each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
"The 'Direct Action' through demonstrations became a regular and often effective event."
For less mobile individuals, this could be replaced by the possibility of expressing opinions electronically; this ranges from internet forums to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are the non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, yet they still seem to be more closely connected to the citizens.
In addition, of course, there is the option to completely disengage and leave politics to the experts in order to focus on other aspects of life.
The latter undoubtedly carries the greatest risks, as it promotes the creeping authoritarianism that is a sign of our times.
But the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also contribute to a rather uncertain situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some would like to break the knot through more direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and the led cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There is still much to be said for holding on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to bring them closer to the people again.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could turn out to be only a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and inject more life into elections and representative governments.
Yet this is probably not enough to restore the general legitimacy that the elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the primary concern of all those for whom freedom is at the heart of the constitution must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
